[SPEAKER_09]: Any questions?

257
00:26:49,319 --> 00:26:50,119
[SPEAKER_09]: Great, wonderful.

258
00:26:50,639 --> 00:26:56,860
[SPEAKER_09]: So at this time I'd like to call up Dr. Talbot so she can give you an update on academics and instruction throughout the city.

259
00:26:59,848 --> 00:27:00,208
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

260
00:27:00,889 --> 00:27:05,372
[SPEAKER_12]: I feel like the last time I was here I had to follow Metallica and now it's Gigi the penguin.

261
00:27:05,412 --> 00:27:10,916
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm starting to feel a little like I should plan my presentations a little better.

262
00:27:11,297 --> 00:27:21,524
[SPEAKER_12]: But tonight's presentation is about how we in Medford are investing in our legacy educators, the educators with caregivers and students.

263
00:27:22,225 --> 00:27:30,394
[SPEAKER_12]: and GG are the things that make Medford really special, and we want to report out how we are taking care of the educators in our district.

264
00:27:30,914 --> 00:27:32,576
[SPEAKER_12]: So tonight I'm gonna talk about two things.

265
00:27:32,796 --> 00:27:40,704
[SPEAKER_12]: One is the state's learning acceleration network in which we're participating, and I would also like to talk about Mustang University.

266
00:27:42,847 --> 00:27:43,047
[SPEAKER_12]: Slide.

267
00:27:45,097 --> 00:28:01,531
[SPEAKER_12]: So thanks to Will, who not only is an ST Math genius, but also does communications for us on the slide, we've rebranded the staff portion of our Medford Public Schools website to Mustang University.

268
00:28:01,611 --> 00:28:08,156
[SPEAKER_12]: We wanted to communicate to staff how much we are investing in them, and this felt like a right next step.

269
00:28:08,937 --> 00:28:21,852
[SPEAKER_12]: So in this rebranding, there are tiles like the professional development screen up here, where staff can easily navigate to what it is that they need to function, I guess, in the district.

270
00:28:22,393 --> 00:28:25,036
[SPEAKER_12]: And so this particular slide, though, is about professional learning.

271
00:28:25,096 --> 00:28:28,059
[SPEAKER_12]: So part of the contract that this body negotiated last year

272
00:28:28,620 --> 00:28:35,246
[SPEAKER_12]: was to reduce some of the half days for professional learning to extended full days of professional learning.

273
00:28:35,766 --> 00:28:46,095
[SPEAKER_12]: Extended full days of professional learning, even though there are fewer, do provide a much richer opportunity for our educators to engage in sustained learning.

274
00:28:46,515 --> 00:28:47,456
[SPEAKER_12]: And that is what we want.

275
00:28:48,076 --> 00:28:55,542
[SPEAKER_12]: So this screen is an example of three of those days and the learning that we provided our educators.

276
00:28:56,483 --> 00:29:02,065
[SPEAKER_12]: So at the beginning of the year, you can see the August 25th PD schedule or a snippet of it.

277
00:29:03,705 --> 00:29:09,607
[SPEAKER_12]: In the middle, you can see the March 3rd offerings that are coming up.

278
00:29:10,288 --> 00:29:15,149
[SPEAKER_12]: And then on the far right, you can see what we offered in November.

279
00:29:15,529 --> 00:29:23,012
[SPEAKER_12]: You can see there were so many offerings in November that we had to split them out by our meet elementary, middle, and high school.

280
00:29:23,903 --> 00:29:26,447
[SPEAKER_12]: and our January 20th PD followed a similar pattern.

281
00:29:27,368 --> 00:29:39,166
[SPEAKER_12]: So we are working hard to invest in educators, providing what they need to feel confident and competent, and also to provide that sense of consistency and coherence that we spoke about in our last meeting.

282
00:29:40,227 --> 00:29:40,527
[SPEAKER_12]: Slide.

283
00:29:40,927 --> 00:29:41,227
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

284
00:29:41,747 --> 00:29:51,809
[SPEAKER_12]: So how we build on belonging, which was the third aspect, right, belonging, consistency, and coherence, is we partner very closely with the MTA.

285
00:29:51,829 --> 00:29:56,550
[SPEAKER_12]: And we have a committee that's called Professional Development Advisory Council.

286
00:29:56,590 --> 00:29:59,991
[SPEAKER_12]: And it's a joint committee with administrators and teachers.

287
00:30:00,631 --> 00:30:05,572
[SPEAKER_12]: And it is the job of this committee to, or this council, to evaluate PD offerings

288
00:30:06,032 --> 00:30:13,795
[SPEAKER_12]: to review feedback, to make recommendations about practices and protocols that impact both teachers and administrators.

289
00:30:14,375 --> 00:30:18,877
[SPEAKER_12]: So what you see on this slide is the feedback form that we've developed this year.

290
00:30:19,497 --> 00:30:23,779
[SPEAKER_12]: We provide this feedback form to all educators at the conclusion of all PD sessions.

291
00:30:24,299 --> 00:30:26,980
[SPEAKER_12]: And then as a committee, we meet and we review the data.

292
00:30:27,060 --> 00:30:34,523
[SPEAKER_12]: We use data-informed practices and protocols and a little help from our generative AI friends to come up with themes in the data.

293
00:30:35,563 --> 00:30:37,944
[SPEAKER_12]: best practices, things that we'd like to see better.

294
00:30:37,964 --> 00:30:53,187
[SPEAKER_12]: And then what our committee does is we produce a couple of slides, you can see them here, to help all of the facilitators of the next upcoming session take our recommendations and show their participants how they are applying them.

295
00:30:53,287 --> 00:31:00,309
[SPEAKER_12]: So in this way, we are building trust and we're committing to the belonging of our educators through the Mustang University.

296
00:31:02,396 --> 00:31:03,137
[SPEAKER_12]: This is a natural pause.

297
00:31:03,157 --> 00:31:04,277
[SPEAKER_12]: Should I keep going or should I pause?

298
00:31:04,798 --> 00:31:05,038
[SPEAKER_12]: Pause.

299
00:31:07,740 --> 00:31:08,120
[SPEAKER_12]: Keep going.

300
00:31:08,921 --> 00:31:09,161
Great.

301
00:31:10,782 --> 00:31:18,828
[SPEAKER_12]: So the last thing I wanted to talk to you about, I alluded to a little bit in our last meeting with the accountability report from the state.

302
00:31:19,709 --> 00:31:28,275
[SPEAKER_12]: And because of performance in a couple of our schools, our district was invited to partner with DESE in a learning acceleration network.

303
00:31:28,655 --> 00:31:30,357
[SPEAKER_12]: They are one of our most valued partners.

304
00:31:31,603 --> 00:31:42,522
[SPEAKER_12]: The program description for the Learning Acceleration Network is that they support district leadership teams to set and achieve goals aligned to a concrete instructional improvement priority.

305
00:31:43,773 --> 00:31:54,639
[SPEAKER_12]: The participants work with consultants, in this case TNTP, to identify a high leverage improvement priority and design a strategy to improve the quality of instruction in a specific subject area.

306
00:31:55,539 --> 00:32:07,946
[SPEAKER_12]: Consultants support the district staff by building their capacity and the capacity of the instructional staff, supporting data collection, progress monitoring, and providing a structure for continuous reflection and improvement.

307
00:32:08,026 --> 00:32:11,528
[SPEAKER_12]: And so that is what we're most excited about in our partnership with DESE.

308
00:32:12,832 --> 00:32:22,324
[SPEAKER_12]: You can see on this slide that we have decided to focus on supporting teachers of ELA in grades three through eight at the McGlynn schools.

309
00:32:23,298 --> 00:32:30,204
[SPEAKER_12]: in the intellectual preparation required to engage learners in grade-level tasks, texts, and tasks.

310
00:32:31,245 --> 00:32:40,353
[SPEAKER_12]: So that focus lets us use strategic resources to brilliant principals in a school with rich, diverse linguistic resources.

311
00:32:40,814 --> 00:32:43,776
[SPEAKER_12]: We can leverage our brilliant directors, Dr. Chiesa and Ms.

312
00:32:43,816 --> 00:32:47,420
[SPEAKER_12]: McNiff in ELA and in EL.

313
00:32:48,100 --> 00:33:05,345
[SPEAKER_12]: We have coaches that we can leverage as part of our instructional team, and we are so excited to be able to build on the foundation that our partnership with the Hill for Literacy, as well as Unbound Ed and Boston College has been able to lay for us with the help of the Barr Foundation.

314
00:33:06,990 --> 00:33:18,217
[SPEAKER_12]: So our team consists of myself and Suzanne and building principals, the ELA and EL directors, instructional coaches, teachers, and Robbie, who is our TNTP consultant.

315
00:33:18,337 --> 00:33:18,878
[SPEAKER_12]: That's our team.

316
00:33:20,359 --> 00:33:21,740
[SPEAKER_12]: So what have we done so far?

317
00:33:21,840 --> 00:33:35,549
[SPEAKER_12]: We've had a couple of high-level planning meetings with senior leadership and with the Department of Education, ensuring coherence among consultants and classroom observations of grades 6 through 8 in ELA and in ELD.

318
00:33:36,369 --> 00:33:37,930
[SPEAKER_12]: We visited the common planning time.

319
00:33:38,030 --> 00:33:38,990
[SPEAKER_12]: Oh, there's lots of acronyms here.

320
00:33:39,010 --> 00:33:39,430
[SPEAKER_12]: I'm so sorry.

321
00:33:39,450 --> 00:33:53,014
[SPEAKER_12]: We visited the common planning time of grades three, four, and five, and we have classroom observations planned in grades three, four, and five so we can really understand what our baseline is of consistent practices.

322
00:33:54,175 --> 00:34:04,438
[SPEAKER_12]: We engage in regular huddles and meetings with Robbie, and that helps us to foster a sense of belonging and confidence, and we cannot wait for this three-year partnership to really take off.

323
00:34:06,871 --> 00:34:09,693
[SPEAKER_12]: And that's how we're supporting educators in Medford Public Schools.

324
00:34:11,074 --> 00:34:11,514
[SPEAKER_12]: Any questions?

325
00:34:12,194 --> 00:34:13,415
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Dr. Talbot.

326
00:34:14,415 --> 00:34:15,636
[SPEAKER_10]: Any questions from the committee?

327
00:34:15,656 --> 00:34:17,437
[SPEAKER_10]: Member Rousseau?

328
00:34:19,318 --> 00:34:20,319
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't actually have questions.

329
00:34:20,359 --> 00:34:34,327
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm just really glad to hear that this is a focus because I know that as a committee we've, you know, we've, and through my time on the school committee, we've talked about hiring practices and really

330
00:34:35,270 --> 00:34:43,695
[SPEAKER_14]: making sure we are keeping the staff that we want as we hire, but the vast majority of staff are not people we are hiring now.

331
00:34:44,195 --> 00:34:53,601
[SPEAKER_14]: So I think that's really good to hear that we're focusing on our, you called them legacy staff, but our, I don't have a better word.

332
00:34:53,681 --> 00:34:58,363
[SPEAKER_14]: So our legacy staff, because they're teaching most of our students.

333
00:34:58,563 --> 00:35:00,625
[SPEAKER_14]: So thank you so much for focusing on that.

334
00:35:04,980 --> 00:35:05,762
[SPEAKER_10]: Member Mastroboni.

335
00:35:05,783 --> 00:35:07,788
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

336
00:35:08,891 --> 00:35:09,553
[SPEAKER_13]: I love seeing this.

337
00:35:09,573 --> 00:35:12,221
[SPEAKER_13]: I love seeing the direct intervention that's

338
00:35:13,591 --> 00:35:16,052
[SPEAKER_13]: pulled directly from what we've seen in state data.

339
00:35:16,553 --> 00:35:19,954
[SPEAKER_13]: You said this is a three year program, three year engagement.

340
00:35:20,895 --> 00:35:29,620
[SPEAKER_13]: Is it likely that, rather like what's our plan to take what we learned in the learning acceleration network and turn it into Mustang Academy?

341
00:35:29,640 --> 00:35:31,761
[SPEAKER_13]: And that's my first question.

342
00:35:31,881 --> 00:35:37,964
[SPEAKER_13]: And the second question is, what's the response been to the sort of PD rebrand?

343
00:35:38,364 --> 00:35:39,485
[SPEAKER_13]: What's the feedback like?

344
00:35:39,605 --> 00:35:41,066
[SPEAKER_13]: And where do you see that going in the future?

345
00:35:42,136 --> 00:35:51,040
[SPEAKER_12]: So I'll take the first question first, which is we absolutely picked the strategic focus for lots of different reasons, and one of them was for scalability.

346
00:35:51,721 --> 00:36:01,245
[SPEAKER_12]: Being able to focus on this group of students, on this group of teachers in this setting, provides us the ability to scale across the middle schools, and also across all the elementary schools.

347
00:36:01,806 --> 00:36:05,027
[SPEAKER_12]: Dr. Chiesa is a K through 12 director, as is Ms.

348
00:36:05,067 --> 00:36:08,189
[SPEAKER_12]: McNiff, so we're able to scale vertically in that way as well.

349
00:36:09,369 --> 00:36:18,694
[SPEAKER_12]: And focusing on this area lets us really leverage the two literacy coaches and the current EL coach of the middle grades to provide maximum impact.

350
00:36:18,734 --> 00:36:23,717
[SPEAKER_12]: It was important to our team and especially the principals to also include teachers on this as well.

351
00:36:23,757 --> 00:36:26,679
[SPEAKER_12]: So we're really investing in teacher leadership.

352
00:36:28,080 --> 00:36:28,801
[SPEAKER_12]: at the state level.

353
00:36:28,901 --> 00:36:44,178
[SPEAKER_12]: So we chose the focus strategically so that we would be able to scale because we know consistent practice across all of our schools and grade levels is what's going to get the Medford students to achieve that economic success and social success that we talked about last meeting.

354
00:36:46,433 --> 00:36:49,054
[SPEAKER_12]: The second question was about the PD rebrand.

355
00:36:49,634 --> 00:36:50,815
[SPEAKER_12]: And so far, so good.

356
00:36:50,855 --> 00:37:01,758
[SPEAKER_12]: I mean, the feedback we're hearing mostly is not what I presented about tonight, but about how we've moved our course reimbursement structure to an online structure, our course pre-approval, our lane advancement.

357
00:37:02,278 --> 00:37:10,441
[SPEAKER_12]: So these things, we're moving from paper to an electronic version so that we're able to track trends over time.

358
00:37:10,521 --> 00:37:15,522
[SPEAKER_12]: We're able to look at the types of courses that our Medford educators are choosing outside of us.

359
00:37:16,262 --> 00:37:20,704
[SPEAKER_12]: And our content directors, as well as the PD committee, is able to look at that data.

360
00:37:21,084 --> 00:37:23,885
[SPEAKER_12]: And it helps us think about what else we need to offer our educators.

361
00:37:23,905 --> 00:37:26,005
[SPEAKER_12]: What are they going outside to seek?

362
00:37:27,026 --> 00:37:29,466
[SPEAKER_12]: And can we offer that in-house instead?

363
00:37:31,847 --> 00:37:34,588
[SPEAKER_12]: So I think that's pretty positive, and I think the website looks pretty snazzy.

364
00:37:34,628 --> 00:37:36,048
[SPEAKER_12]: So my feedback is pretty good on that.

365
00:37:36,088 --> 00:37:36,588
[SPEAKER_09]: Dr. Galussi?

366
00:37:37,928 --> 00:37:39,449
[SPEAKER_09]: I was just going to add on one other thing.

367
00:37:40,649 --> 00:37:48,410
[SPEAKER_09]: Additionally to your first question, part of our internal conversations are also looking at curriculum at the secondary level.

368
00:37:48,470 --> 00:38:01,173
[SPEAKER_09]: So I think the partnership here is also going to be assisting us with taking a little bit of a deeper dive at what curriculum is being used at six through eight.

369
00:38:02,213 --> 00:38:06,515
[SPEAKER_09]: so that we can make sure that we have high quality instructional materials in front of our students.

370
00:38:09,977 --> 00:38:10,277
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

371
00:38:10,297 --> 00:38:10,978
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

372
00:38:11,078 --> 00:38:11,658
[SPEAKER_10]: Member Reinfeld.

373
00:38:13,379 --> 00:38:14,079
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you so much.

374
