[SPEAKER_15]: You anticipated my question about what feedback we're getting from participants on the professional development.

375
00:38:20,570 --> 00:38:39,660
[SPEAKER_15]: I am just curious how this focused attention on ELA, which I think is fabulous and I understand the reasoning there, how that affects growth and professional development in subject areas, particularly for elementary teachers who are teaching across all the subjects.

376
00:38:39,700 --> 00:38:44,042
[SPEAKER_15]: Because we as a district have invested a lot in ELA and early literacy.

377
00:38:44,722 --> 00:38:53,274
[SPEAKER_15]: and curriculum and coaches and all of that and I think that's fantastic and I don't want to lose that but I also want to make sure other subjects aren't getting left behind.

378
00:38:53,755 --> 00:38:58,241
[SPEAKER_12]: Such a great question because our data says lots of subject areas could use this.

379
00:38:58,722 --> 00:38:59,863
[SPEAKER_12]: So the instructional focus

380
00:39:01,720 --> 00:39:05,742
[SPEAKER_12]: Like when we talk about our ELA curriculum, we don't teach books, we teach skills.

381
00:39:06,262 --> 00:39:18,027
[SPEAKER_12]: So even though our focus is embedded in ELA as like a frame, the actual focus is supporting teachers and the intellectual preparation required to leverage grade level content and tasks.

382
00:39:18,287 --> 00:39:24,930
[SPEAKER_12]: And so that skill applies across all of the disciplines, especially for our elementary teachers who, as you say,

383
00:39:25,550 --> 00:39:26,911
[SPEAKER_12]: They are doing heroic work, right?

384
00:39:26,951 --> 00:39:32,074
[SPEAKER_12]: They have to be experts in ELA, math, social studies, and science.

385
00:39:32,494 --> 00:39:40,398
[SPEAKER_12]: And this work, this intellectual preparation work, when they sit down with high quality instruction materials, is a skill that transfers across all of the disciplines.

386
00:39:40,938 --> 00:39:43,019
[SPEAKER_12]: So that's why we picked this as opposed to...

387
00:39:44,360 --> 00:39:50,444
[SPEAKER_12]: program implementation or like foundational skills in ELA, this particular skill is widely transferable.

388
00:39:50,784 --> 00:39:57,888
[SPEAKER_15]: And are they having the opportunity to actually have that conversation and reflection and think about specifically how it applies to other subjects?

389
00:39:57,908 --> 00:40:05,273
[SPEAKER_15]: Because a lot of the professional development I've done, if you don't build that time in to explicitly think about how it applies to this situation.

390
00:40:06,672 --> 00:40:07,752
[SPEAKER_12]: It stays abstract.

391
00:40:07,792 --> 00:40:08,032
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah.

392
00:40:08,652 --> 00:40:09,313
[SPEAKER_12]: I am hoping so.

393
